  <h2>Understanding Hard Water and Why It Matters</h2>
  <p>Hard water contains elevated concentrations of dissolved minerals — primarily calcium and magnesium — picked up as groundwater passes through limestone, chalk, and dolomite formations. While not a health hazard (and potentially beneficial in moderate amounts), hard water creates practical problems that affect daily life:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Scale buildup:</strong> White, chalky deposits accumulate on faucets, showerheads, and inside pipes, water heaters, and appliances. Over time, scale reduces pipe diameter and appliance efficiency, increasing energy bills and shortening equipment lifespan.</li>
    <li><strong>Poor taste:</strong> Water above 300 TDS often tastes mineral-heavy, chalky, or slightly metallic. Coffee and tea taste noticeably different (worse) made with hard water.</li>
    <li><strong>Soap inefficiency:</strong> Hard water minerals react with soap, creating scum instead of suds. You use more soap, shampoo, and detergent, and dishes and laundry may not feel fully clean.</li>
    <li><strong>Dry skin and hair:</strong> Hard water deposits mineral film on skin and hair, causing dryness, irritation, and dull-looking hair.</li>
    <li><strong>Shortened filter life:</strong> Hard water clogs all filter types faster, increasing replacement costs. This is especially impactful for pitcher filters that have limited capacity.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>TDS (Total Dissolved Solids) is the most commonly used measure for hard water. A simple TDS meter ($10-15) gives you an instant reading in parts per million (ppm). Below 150 ppm is considered soft to moderately hard; above 300 ppm is hard; above 500 ppm is very hard and typically warrants treatment.</p>

  <h2>What to Look For in a Hard Water Filter</h2>
  <p>Treating hard water for drinking requires specific filtration technologies. Standard carbon filters and most pitcher filters do not remove hardness minerals. Here is what works:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Reverse osmosis:</strong> The most effective method for reducing TDS in drinking water. RO membranes reject 93-99% of dissolved minerals. The iSpring RCC7AK and Waterdrop G3P600 are our top RO picks for hard water.</li>
    <li><strong>Ion exchange (ZeroWater):</strong> ZeroWater's 5-stage ion exchange process strips TDS to 0 ppm — the most complete mineral removal of any pitcher filter. The trade-off is dramatically shortened filter life in hard water.</li>
    <li><strong>Water softeners (whole-house):</strong> Traditional salt-based softeners replace calcium and magnesium with sodium through ion exchange. They address the whole-house scale problem but add sodium to drinking water, which is why many people pair a softener with an RO system for drinking.</li>
    <li><strong>Note on standard carbon filters:</strong> Brita Standard, Amazon Basics, and similar carbon/ion exchange pitcher filters do NOT significantly reduce hardness or TDS. They improve taste by removing chlorine but leave mineral content largely unchanged.</li>
  </ul>

  <ProTip title="Test Your Water Before You Buy">
    Buy a TDS meter ($10-15 on Amazon) and test your tap water before purchasing a filter. If your TDS is under 200 ppm, a standard pitcher filter may be sufficient for taste improvement. Between 200-400 ppm, consider ZeroWater for small volumes or an RO system for higher usage. Above 400 ppm, reverse osmosis is the only cost-effective long-term solution — ZeroWater filters will last only 1-2 weeks at these levels, making the per-gallon cost prohibitive.
  </ProTip>

